The '''Abbotsford Club''' was a [[text publication society]] founded in [[Edinburgh]] in 1833<ref name=Matthews>{{cite book|last=Matthews|first=David|title=The Making of Middle English, 1765–1910|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|year=1999|pages=88&ndash;90|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AlZKopZ9TZUC&pg=PA88|isbn=0-8166-3185-9}}</ref> or 1834.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Oxford Companion to English Literature |edition=6th |editor-first=Margaret |editor-last=Drabble |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |year=2000 |page=1 |isbn=9780198662440 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Ward|first=Adolphus William|author2=Alfred Rayney Waller|title=The Cambridge History of English Literature|publisher=CUP Archive|year=1960|edition=reprint|page=358|isbn=0-546-67017-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Fas8AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA358}}</ref> This was the year after the death of Sir [[Walter Scott]], whose residence of [[Abbotsford House]] gave the society its name, and whose literature the club's publications sought to illuminate. The club was modelled on the [[Roxburghe Club]], of which Scott himself had been a member, as well as the [[Bannatyne Club]], which was founded by Scott, and the [[Glasgow]]-centred [[Maitland Club]]. The founder and first secretary of the club was [[William Barclay Turnbull]], a young Edinburgh lawyer. The stated objective of the Abbotsford Club was "the printing of Miscellaneous Pieces, illustrative of History, Literature, and Antiquities".<ref name=Matthews/> Through its publishing activity, the club did much to promote the proliferation of [[Middle English]] literature. The Abbotsford Club effectively ceased publication in 1866.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://5hm1h4aktue2uejbs1hsqt31-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/abbotsfordclub.pdf |publisher=Royal Historical Society |title=Abbotsford Club publications (listing) |accessdate=29 March 2018 }}</ref>
The club was housed at 25 Great King Street in [[New Town, Edinburgh|Edinburgh's Second New Town]].<ref>''Edinburgh and Leith Post Office Directory'' 1845.</ref>
The complete publications of the Abbotsford Club are available online from the [[National Library of Scotland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://digital.nls.uk/84240851|title=Abbotsford Club, Publications by Scottish clubs|last=|first=|date=|website=National Library of Scotland|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-11-21}}</ref>
