{{refimprove|date=December 2011}}
{{Infobox book | name = Epic Level Handbook | image = Epic level hndbk v3 cover.jpg | image_size = 250px | caption = Epic Level Handbook for D&D v3. | author = [[Andy Collins (game designer)|Andy Collins]] and [[Bruce R. Cordell]] | genre = [[Role-playing game]] | publisher = [[Wizards of the Coast]] | release_date = 2001 | media_type = Print ([[Hardback]]) | pages = 320 | isbn = 0-7869-2658-9 }}
The '''''Epic Level Handbook''''' is a rule-book by [[Wizards of the Coast]] for the [[Dungeons & Dragons 3rd edition|3rd edition]] of ''[[Dungeons & Dragons]]''. The book was published in 2001, and contains optional game rules for playing [[player characters|characters]] who have reached a higher [[Level (role-playing games)#Level-based progression|experience level]] than is covered in the standard rules. This is referred to in the book as "[[epic level]]" play.
== Contents ==
The ''Epic Level Handbook'' contains rules for [[player characters|characters]] to attain levels above 20, the highest level covered by the rules in the ''[[Player's Handbook]]'' and ''[[Dungeon Master's Guide]]'', the core rule-books for the game. It provides [[Epic level|epic-level progression]] information for all the core [[Character class (Dungeons & Dragons)|classes]], the [[Prestige Classes|prestige classes]] from the ''Dungeon Master's Guide'', and the [[Psionics (Dungeons & Dragons)|psionic]] classes from the ''[[Psionics Handbook]]''. It also provides new epic-level prestige classes, magical items, monsters and "Epic Spells", all of which follow somewhat different rules than the standard game.
== Publication history ==
The ''Epic Level Handbook'' was designed by [[Andy Collins (game designer)|Andy Collins]] and [[Bruce R. Cordell]], and published in 2001. The cover art is by [[Arnie Swekel]], with interior art by Daren Bader, [[Gerald Brom|Brom]], [[David Day (artist)|David Day]], [[Brian Despain]], [[Larry Dixon (fantasy artist)|Larry Dixon]], Michael Dutton, [[Jeff Easley]], [[Lars Grant-West]], [[Rebecca Guay]], [[Jeremy Jarvis]], Alton Lawson, [[Todd Lockwood]], [[David L. Martin|David Martin]], [[Raven Mimura]], [[Matthew Mitchell (artist)|Matthew Mitchell]], [[Vinod Rams]], [[Wayne Reynolds]], Darrell Riche, [[Richard Sardinha]], Marc Sasso, [[Mark Smylie]], Arnie Swekel, and [[Anthony S. Waters|Anthony Waters]].
Collins was the first designer scheduled for the book, and handled the core of the rules, while Cordell handled the epic spellcasting and epic monsters.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=dnd/ps/20020712a| title=Product Spotlight: Epic Level Handbook| date=July 17, 2002| publisher=[[Wizards of the Coast]]| accessdate=August 1, 2013| last=Ryan| first=Michael}}</ref>
The book was updated for the 3.5 edition via an update document available from the Wizards of the Coast website.
The 4th Edition covers this in an alternate manner with continuous 1-30 level progress. WotC covered the topic in their 2009 conference.<ref name="level 30">{{cite web|url=http://www.critical-hits.com/blog/2009/08/07/4th-edition-dd-beyond-level-30/|title=Beyond Level 30|last=Rupp|first=Danny|date=August 7, 2009|website=|publisher=Critical Hits|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=2011-07-03}}</ref> (need more details)
== Reception ==
The reviewer from ''[[Pyramid (magazine)|Pyramid]]'' commented that before the ''Epic Level Handbook'', the third edition did not make it easy to play powerful characters, especially compared to prior editions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sjgames.com/pyramid/sample.html?id=2936 |title=Pyramid: Pyramid Review: The Epic Level Handbook (for Dungeons & Dragons) |publisher=Sjgames.com |date=2002-08-09 |accessdate=2014-05-26}}</ref> Another reviewer commented that the book "addresses how to keep the ''Dungeons & Dragons'' system functioning after 20th level. Due to the nature of the system, many conventions of the system such as save and attack bonus conventions do not work as well if extrapolated out past 20th level."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sjgames.com/pyramid/sample.html?id=3590 |title=Pyramid: Review of Epic Level Handbook |publisher=Sjgames.com |date=2002-08-14 |accessdate=2014-05-26}}</ref>
James Voelpel from mania.com commented: "A landmark book from Wizards of the Coast, the ''Epic Level Handbook'' not only helps dungeon masters run high level games but encourages smart players to strive for it's {{sic}} unlimited greatness."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mania.com/handbooks-sourcebooks-novelsoh-my_article_36518.html |title=Handbooks and Sourcebooks and Novels...Oh My! |publisher=Mania.com |date=October 13, 2002 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227081234/http://www.mania.com/handbooks-sourcebooks-novelsoh-my_article_36518.html |archivedate=February 27, 2015}}</ref>
