{{Unsourced|date=June 2013}}
In '''''S v Morrison''''', an important case in [[South Africa|South African]] [[Criminal procedure in South Africa|criminal procedure]], the court considered whether or not there is a duty on the presiding officer to inform the accused of his [[Right to counsel|right to legal representation]].
In terms of section 73(2) of the [[Criminal Procedure Act, 1977|CPA]], the accused has a right to legal representation, but the court held that this right is generally known to most people, and that no rule of law or practice requires a trial court to spell this out to every unrepresented accused.
The court held that whether there is such a duty depends on the circumstances of the case.
This case was heard before the [[Constitution of South Africa|Constitution]] came into force. The Constitution now explicitly protects the right of the accused to be informed of his right to legal representation.
